{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2hayden_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280605049/1949061701/0140.xml":{"full_text":"Jaycees Give Awards\nTo Youth Welfare and\nBulletin Committees\nThe youth welfare committee\nand' bulletin committee of the\nWashington Junior Board of\nCommerce yesterday were pre\nsented awards for outstanding\nwork during the past year.\nAt a luncheon in the Burlington\nHotel, President-elect Paul Mat\nhews presented the organization\u2019s\nplaque to John W. Costello, chair\nman of the youth committee, and\nJames D. Bligh, Jr., new vice presi\ndent, presented a similar award to\nTheodore N. McDowell, editor of\nthe group\u2019s publication, the \"Bul\nletin.\u201d\nThrough the Youth weiiare\nCommittee, Mr. Costello has done\n\u201cone of the most outstanding Jobs\nIn the history of the board,\u201d Mr.\nMatthews said. Projects of the\ncommittee Included the Walter\nJohnson Baseball School, Christ\nmas parties, child guidance, the\njunior Olympics and the Crippled\nChildren\u2019s Boat Ride.\n\"Director in charge\u201d of the\nyouth committe was Patrick M.\nDoming, of the Federal Storage\nCo.\nIn presenting the plaque to Mr.\nMcDowell, a reporter for The Star\nwho recently was elected a di\nrector of the Junior board, Mr.\nBligh cited the fact that the Bulle\ntin recently won third place in na\ntional competition among similar\npublications. He also lauded toe\nYork of Thomas Amatucci, Jr.,\nBulletin director and new second\nTice president.\nMr. Bligh of the John Han\ncock Life Insurance Co. himself\nwas awarded the \u201cJames 8. Beat\ntie Award\u201d for \"outstanding mem\nber of the year. Mr. Beattie is\na past president.\nThe citation for \u2018\u2018outstanding\nproject of the year,\u201d which goes\nto toe Arthur 8. Fleming Govern\nment Award program, will be pre\nsented to Harry Bergmann of\nRiggs National Bank, who was not\npresent at yesterday\u2019s ceremonies.\nWork of toe committee was to\nobtain \u201crecognition\u201d for Govern\nment employes doing outstanding\nservice.\nAn award for \u201cman of the\nmonth\u201d of May went to Kenneth\nClarke of the Guardian Life In\nsurance Co. He has been active\non \u201cJust about every committee\ntoe Junior board has,\u201d F. Elwood\nDavis, retiring president, said.\nNew officers, elected June 6,\nalso were Installed yesterday. In\naddition to Mr. Matthews, Mr.\nBligh and Mr. Amatucci, they\nare Thomas Sheehan, secretary:\nFrank C. Frantz, treasurer, and\nCarleton Edwards, general counsel.\nWaltham to Add 1,800\nfo Payroll, Official Says\n\u2022y th\u00ab Anatloted frm*\nWALTHAM, Mass.. June IT\u2014\nThe man In charge of reorganiz\ning the Waltham Watch Co. zays\nthere will be 1.800 persons o*#*'\nfayrbll by next week.\nJohn J. Haggerty, former J66*1\nconstruction Finance Corp. offi\ncial appointed to handle the Wal\ntham firm, added that \"the banks\nwill be paid in full\u201d by next week.\nMr. Haggerty denied that the\ncompany hired him while the RFC\nloan was being applied for. In\nWashington, a Senate Banking\nSubcommittee has been urged to\nrequire that any firm seeking an\nRFC loan must agree not to hire\nany RFC official for the next five\nyears.\nThe Waltham situation was\ncited as an example by Senator\nFulbright, Democrat, of Arkansas.\n\u201cI wasn\u2019t appointed by the RFC,\nbut by the trustees (of the watch\nArm) with the approval of a Fed\neral Judge,\u201d Mr. Haggerty said.\n\u201cThe RFC interposed no objec\ntion.\u201d\nHe said his new job had no\nconnection with his previous as\nsociation with the RFC.\nIII. I I II\nREPORTER RECETVE8 AWARD\u2014Theodore N. McDowell (left) a reporter for The Star, receive*\na Junior Board of Commerce plaque for work a* editor of the chamber1* publication, the\nBulletin, from James D. BUgh, Jr, new rice president. Looking on la P. Elwood Darla (right),\nretiring president.*\u2014Star 8taff Photo.\nTwo Missouri Ministers Fight\nOver Performance of Wedding\nSy th* Au*ciat*d Prw*\nROCKPORT, Mo., June 17\u2014A\nPresbyterian pastor today nursed\nan Injured nose\u2014the result of a\none-pnuch dispute with a Meth\nodist minister.\nThe argument was over which\npreacher would perform a mar\nriage ceremony.\nThe Rev. Ellis J. Hough, pastor\nof the Third Presbyterian Church\nin Kansas City, suffered the nose\ninjury.\nrne incident was reiatea yester\nday after the Rev. Kenneth J.\nBressler of the Methodist Church,\nin Fairfax, Mo\u201e was fined $25 In\nMagistrate Court on a plea of\nguilty to common assault.\nMr. Hough said he planned to\nsue Mr. Bressler \"for $10,000 per\nsonal injuries.\u201d He said his nose\nwas broken.\nThe incident occurred last Sun\nday shortly before James Richard\nSchoemann and Miss Wilma\nJacqueline Wright were to be\nmarried in Mr. Bressler\u2019s ehurch.\nThe bride, a Methodist, wanted\nthe wedding in Mr. Bossier\u2019s\nchurch, but agreed with the bride\ngroom, a Presbyterian, that Mr.\nHough should read the service.\nMr. Sbugh said he asked Mr.\nBressleO permission and \u201creceived\na rather vituperative letter from\nhim^ M didn\u2019t like the idea, but\nrequested me to call on him when\nI arrived in Fairfax.\u201d\nThe argument began whsxt Mr.\nHough arrived at Mr. Bressler\u2019s\nhome. t\nSaid Mr. Bressler:\nireatened to send $he\ntten him to the Meth\nj, and I wanted it\nWidow Receives Air Medal\nFor Lt. Gen. Daniel Sultan\nAn air medal awarded posthum\nously to Lt. Ge*h. Daniel I. Sultan\nhas been presented to his widow.\nMrs. Florence B. Sultan, 3133\nConnecticut avenue N.W.\nThe Military District of Wash\nington said the award was \u201cfor\nsuperior leadership and excep\ntional courage\" displayed by the\ngeneral while serving first as dep\nuty and later as commander in\nthe India-Burma theater during\nthe war.\nA former District Engineer\nCommissioner, Gen. Sultan was\nArmy inspector general when he\ndied in Walter Reed Hospital in\nJanuary, 1947.\nMaj. Gen. Hobart R. Gay, mili\ntary district commander, pre\nsented the award.\nSALE\nMEN\u2019S\nSLACKS\nSlack Trousers, well\ntailored, ideal for\ncasual wear\ntow-priced\nFormerly >9.95\n725 12th ST. N.W. oSSTL\nback. I cot mad\u2014a fit of temper,\nJust like anybody can vet once in\na while\u2014and X struck him, just\nonce.\"\nAfter the dispute neither min\nister performed the ceremony.\nA third pastor, the Rev. Harold\nPark, jr\u201e of the Fairfax Presbyte\nrian Church, was called In for the\nmarriage.\nCommissioners Re-Elect\nYoung as Chairman\nCommissioner John Russell\nYoung was re-elected chairman\nof the Board of Commissioners\nyesterday at a meeting of the city,\nheads.\nMr. Young's re-appointment for\na fourth term as Commissioner\nwas confirmed Monday by the\nSenate. He took his oath of office\nWednesday.\nTextile Union Drops\nPay Demands Because\nOf Business Slump\nSr Vvm\nNEW YORK, June 17\u2014A Wi\nthe union ha* decided not to seek\nwage increase* for 1X0 000 work\ners\u2014because of poor business a\nthe cot tor -rayon tedustry\nA policy committee of the CIO\nTextile Workers' Union said yes\nterday it reached Ha decision \"with\ngreat reluctance.\u201d\nMoat of the union's member*\nwork a New England textile mill*\nOthers are scattered in mills a\nMiddle Atlantic and Western\nState*.\nThe committee's statement said\n\"Justice alone would demand a\nwage Increase, but justice must\nyield, momentarily, to the gnm\nfacts. No purpose would be served\nby the expensive gesture of an\nother losing arbitration.\"\nLast January, an arbitrator re\nfused to grant a union request for\na 10-eent hourly wage boost. Tbs\ncommittee said he undoubtedly\nwould turn the union down again\nbecause business remains poor.\nThe committee blamed the tex\ntile drop on management's short\nsighted price and profit policy\nafter the destruction of price\ncontrol.\"\nUnder Its contract, the union\nmay reopen wage negotiations in\nSeptember. Wage demands must\nbe arbitrated. According to the\nunion, the present wage averages\n11.20 hourly, with a \u00bb7-eent\nminimum.\nThe committee said Its decisions\nare advisory, and local unions may\nact on their own if they wish\nHowever, locals normally abide by\nPulley Committee recommenda\ntions.\nTrain Crash Kills 1, Hurts 10\nCIUDAD TRUJILLO, Dominican\nRepublic. June 17 (A*).\u2014One per\nson was killed and 10 Injured yes\nterday when a 62-car freight train\ncarrying 2.000 tons of sugar cane\nleft the tracks. Wornout rails were\nblamed for the accident.\nt/Ae ofi /VaZu>tta\u00a3\u00a3\u00a3 ^amoad Meno CUea/i\n\nSUGGESTIONS.\nFor Lost MfmUe Shoppers\nUNUSUAL\nFat\nGIFTS FROM UNIVERSITY SHOP\nA NEW SENSATlSN''\n\"COPAVERRA\"\nlllal Marshall of Miami\nDod will be crazy about thii newest Mol\nMarshall style creation that combines\ntop fashion and top comfort. Six colon\nto choose from.\nonly $J2'50\nI\n'VERI-COOL\"\nDRESS'N PLAY SHIRT\nLooking cool is one 'thing being cool\nis the important thing. Here is the\nperfect shirt for both. Mesh weove in\nwhite oitd solid colors. Sizes 14-17.\nAngle collar with stoys... holf sleeves.\nonly \u00a3^*95\nNEW SHIPMENT\nJUST ARRIVED\ni\nSPORT SHIRT\nThe latest in cool styling end comfort in\nthis fine washable royon shirt. You'll find\nDod's size in Blue and Navy, Grey and Navy,\nTan ond Brown, and Moise and Brown,\nonly $4-95\nUniversity Sikh*\n1318 G STREET. N.W.\nMS GIFT WAAFFING FAME FAAKJNG AT CAFTTAL GAAAGA\n\nIT'S A NATURAL\nRI6HT AT\nTHE START OF\nTHE SEASON!\nEvery Bell\nSummer Suit\nREDUCED!\n$35 *40\nAll-Wool\nTROPICAL\nWORSTEDS\nAnd Notionolly Famous Wrinkle-Resistant Summer Suits\ni\nGentlemen! If you want a cool, comfortable\nwrinkle resistant summer suit at a reduced price,\nthen by all means be in our store tomorrow. You\u2019ll\nsee hundreds and hundreds of garments in every\nnew color and pattern hit. You find all sizes for\nregulars, longs, shorts, stouts, and slims. And\nbest of all, you\u2019ll find that Bell Clothes price tags\n\u2022are more than fair to any pocket book.\nWHITE FORMAL COATS.24.85\nMEN'S SPORT COATS.17.8